{"title_page": "No Pretendo", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=June 2015}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = No Pretendo\n| cover      = Gloria_Estefan_No_Pretendo_Single.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Gloria Estefan]]\n| album      = [[Destiny (Gloria Estefan album)|Destiny]]\n| released   = 1997\n| format     = [[CD single]]\n| recorded   = 1995-1996\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Latin Pop]]\n| length     = 3:47\n| label      = [[Epic Records|Epic]]\n| writer     = [[Kike Santander]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title = [[Show Me the Way Back to Your Heart]]\n| prev_year  = 1997\n| next_title = [[En El Jard\u00edn]]\n| next_year  = 1997\n}}\n\n'''\"No Pretendo\"''' (\"I Don't Pretend To\") is a 1997 song by American singer and songwriter [[Gloria Estefan]]. It was released as the sixth and final single from her seventh studio album, ''[[Destiny (Gloria Estefan album)|Destiny]]''. This song is the Spanish-language version of the song \"Steal Your Heart\", from [[Destiny (Gloria Estefan album)|''Destiny'']]. It was released on international editions of the album, as well as a single in the United States and Spain, where the single peaked at number 28. The music video was recorded live from the ''[[Evolution World Tour]]'' in Mexico City at the [[Estadio Azteca]]. In 2004, \"No pretendo\" was made available on the compilations, ''[[Amor y Suerte: Exitos Romanticos|Amor y Suerte: \u00c9xitos Rom\u00e1nticos]]'', and ''[[Oye Mi Canto!: Los Grandes Exitos]]'' in 2006.\n\n==Charts==\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Chart (1997)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n|Spain ([[Productores de M\u00fasica de Espa\u00f1a|AFYVE]])\n|align=\"center\"|28\n|-\n|U.S. Billboard Hot Latin Tracks\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|-\n|U.S. Billboard Latin Pop Airplay\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|-\n|U.S. Billboard Latin Tropical/Salsa Airplay\n|align=\"center\"|4\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Number-one hits of 1997 (U.S. Hot Latin Tracks)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ooltra.net/Lyrics.php?a=GloriaEstefan&s=NoPretendo Lyrics with English translation]\n* {{MetroLyrics song|gloria-estefan|no-pretendo}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Gloria Estefan}}\n{{Gloria Estefan singles}}\n\n[[Category:1997 singles]]\n[[Category:Gloria Estefan songs]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language songs]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot Latin Songs number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Kike Santander]]\n[[Category:1996 songs]]\n[[Category:Epic Records singles]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=June 2015}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = No Pretendo\n| cover      = Gloria_Estefan_No_Pretendo_Single.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Gloria Estefan]]\n| album      = [[Destiny (Gloria Estefan album)|Destiny]]\n| released   = 1997\n| format     = [[CD single]]\n| recorded   = 1995-1996\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Latin Pop]]\n| length     = 3:47\n| label      = [[Epic Records|Epic]]\n| writer     = [[Kike Santander]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title = [[Show Me the Way Back to Your Heart]]\n| prev_year  = 1997\n| next_title = [[En El Jard\u00edn]]\n| next_year  = 1997\n}}\n\n'''\"No Pretendo\"''' (\"I Don't Pretend To\") is a 1997 song by American singer and songwriter [[Gloria Estefan]]. It was released as the sixth and final single from her seventh studio album, ''[[Destiny (Gloria Estefan album)|Destiny]]''. This song is the Spanish language version of the song \"Steal Your Heart\", from [[Destiny (Gloria Estefan album)|''Destiny'']]. It was released on international editions of the album, as well as a single in the United States and Spain, where the single peaked at number 28. The music video was recorded live from the ''[[Evolution World Tour]]'' in Mexico City at the [[Estadio Azteca]]. In 2004, \"No pretendo\" was made available on the compilations, ''[[Amor y Suerte: Exitos Romanticos|Amor y Suerte: \u00c9xitos Rom\u00e1nticos]]'', and ''[[Oye Mi Canto!: Los Grandes Exitos]]'' in 2006.\n\n==Charts==\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Chart (1997)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n|Spain ([[Productores de M\u00fasica de Espa\u00f1a|AFYVE]])\n|align=\"center\"|28\n|-\n|U.S. Billboard Hot Latin Tracks\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|-\n|U.S. Billboard Latin Pop Airplay\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|-\n|U.S. Billboard Latin Tropical/Salsa Airplay\n|align=\"center\"|4\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Number-one hits of 1997 (U.S. Hot Latin Tracks)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ooltra.net/Lyrics.php?a=GloriaEstefan&s=NoPretendo Lyrics with English translation]\n* {{MetroLyrics song|gloria-estefan|no-pretendo}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Gloria Estefan}}\n{{Gloria Estefan singles}}\n\n[[Category:1997 singles]]\n[[Category:Gloria Estefan songs]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language songs]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot Latin Songs number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Kike Santander]]\n[[Category:1996 songs]]\n[[Category:Epic Records singles]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:replaced: Spanish language \u2192 Spanish-language", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/No_Pretendo"}
{"title_page": "Sharifu Kiragga Tusuubira", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=March 2020}}\n\n{{short description|Uganda's sickle cell advocates}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Sharifu Kiragga Tusuubira\n| image       = Sharif Kiragga Tusuubira.jpg\n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = {{birth-date and age|January 4, 1991}}\n| birth_place = [[Kampala, Uganda]]\n| occupation  = Biomedical scientist, sickle cell advocate\n| spouse      = Sophia Nalubowa\n| parents     = Ashadu Zizinga and Ritah  Bazanya\n}}\n\n'''Sharifu Kiragga Tusuubira''' (born January 4, 1991) is one of Uganda's leading [[sickle cell]] advocates.<ref>Uganda young leaders-US Embassy, Kampala. [https://ug.usembassy.gov/ambassador-malac-parliament-speaker-rebecca-kadaga-flag-off-2017-yali-washington-mandela-fellows-uganda/ \"Speaker of Parliament, Uganda and US Ambassador to Uganda flag off, Mandela Fellows\" ] June 15, 2017,</ref> He is best recognized for his role in starting community sickle cell screening in [[Uganda]]. An initiative that enables people to take the sickle cell [[Screening (medicine)|screening test]] and receive results instantly from the confines of their villages.\n\n==Biography==\n\nSharifu was born on January 4, 1991, in Kampala to Ashadu Zizinga, a health inspector and Ritah Bazanya, a police officer.\nSharifu received his bachelor's degree in biomedical medical technology from [[Makerere University]] in 2012. He later went on to graduate with a master's degree in biomedical laboratory science and management from the same university.  In 2017, he attended the Civic Leadership Institute at [[Kansas State University]].<ref>, Staley School of Leadership Studies [https://www.k-state.edu/today/announcement/?id=35106 \"Staley School of Leadership Studies to host Mandela Washington Fellows\"] June 13, 2017,</ref><ref>[https://blogs.k-state.edu/leadership/2017/10/12/mandela-washington-fellows-2017-civic-leadership-institute/ Mandela Washington Fellows: 2017 Civic Leadership Institute] October 12, 2017,</ref>\nHe was the first Executive Director of the Uganda Sickle Cell Rescue Foundation (USCRF)  a [[non-profit organization]] working to promote awareness, sensitization and fighting Sickle Cell Disease in Uganda <ref>The International Research & Exchanges Board [https://www.irex.org/people/sharifu-kiragga-tusuubira \"Sharifu Kiragga Tusuubira\"] March 2017</ref> (a position he held until July 2019).\n\n==Sickle Cell advocacy==\nSharifu Kiragga Tusuubira is a strong proponent for and an advocate of sickle cell and [[disability rights]] in Uganda.  His advocacy started while at [[Makerere University]] , following a personal heartbreak moment where a lady he was in love with, rejected him because of sickle cell. This motivated Sharifu to get involved and change the status quo of how the sickle cell was viewed.<ref>The Sickle Cell Warrior Diary [https://medium.com/@thewarriordiaries/the-journey-of-hope-from-wandegeya-to-america-sharifu-tusuubira-b24c3aefcfc3 \"The journey of HOPE from Wandegeya to America\"] September 27, 2019,</ref>\n\nFor over eight years, Sharifu has advocated for people living with sickle cell disease to have rights to independent thinking, participate freely in community activities or further Agency and enjoy the same privileges as the \u2018normal\u2019 people in Uganda <ref>Young African Leaders Initiative [https://yali.state.gov/yali-voices-sharifu-tusuubira-champions-cause-living-sickle-cell-disease/ \"YALI Voices Podcast: Sharifu Tusuubira champions the cause of those living with sickle cell disease\"] December 2018,</ref><ref>The Daily Monitor [https://www.monitor.co.ug/Magazines/HealthLiving/Hope-for-sickle-cells-patients/689846-3282908-2e3i30/index.html \"Hope for Sickle Cell patients\"] July 7, 2016,</ref><ref>The Daily Monitor [https://www.monitor.co.ug/Magazines/HealthLiving/Medical-options-for-people-with-sickle-cell-anaemia/689846-2429224-1407nqs/index.html\"Medical Options for people living with sickle cell\"] August 14, 2014,</ref><ref>Uganda Sickle Cell Rescue Foundation [https://www.uscrfuganda.org/my-burden-is-my-purpose-without-it-i-wouldnt-be/\"My burden is my purpose\"] September 4, 2017,</ref><ref>Biomedical Central Public health [https://bmcpublichealth.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s12889-018-5496-4\"Knowledge, perception and practices towards sickle cell disease\"] April 27, 2018,</ref><ref>Adolescent health medicine and therapeutics [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6778728/\"To Join Or Not To Join? A Case Of Sickle Cell Clubs, Stigma And Discrimination In Secondary Schools In Butambala District, Uganda\"] October 2, 2019,</ref>\n\nLiving with sickle cell, Sharifu provides a firsthand narrative through his lived experiences to address issues of care, behavior, stigma, and discrimination among persons with sickle cell in different locales. Sharifu reached over 60,150 people, set up 18 support networks and registered 20,153 across the Uganda.<ref>Global Thinkers Forum [http://globalthinkersmentors.org/sharifu-tusuubira-1 \"Leaders of Tomorrow - Sharifu Tusuubira\"] October 2018</ref> \n \nAcross the region, Sharifu has played a key role in supporting sickle cell advocacy.<ref>Betty Amamukirori [https://www.newvision.co.ug/new_vision/news/1424076/businessmen-contribute-sh50m-sickle-cell-fight \"Businessmen contribute sh50m towards sickle cell fight\"] ''New Vision Uganda'' 8th May 2016</ref><ref>John Muto-Ono P [http://www.blackstarnews.com/health/health/uganda-moves-to-fight-sickle-cell-disease-one-testing-site-serving \"Uganda moves to fight sickle cell disease\"] ''Blackstar news, Uganda'' June 21st, 2016</ref> Sharifu was instrumental in the launch of the East Africa Sickle Cell Alliance. He worked with the Pan African Sickle Cell Federation International to support grassroots initiatives and build membership across East and Central Africa.<ref>Gilmore Tee Show. Cliff Central.  South Africa [https://iono.fm/e/573872?fbclid=IwAR1lyGw_uNynvBaINU99uzisXJaL1prWlADfxRnyw6w6yUmcrO1TOjOEWdU \"World Sickle Cell Day\"] 22 Jun 2018</ref>\nSharifu is a 2017 Mandela Washington Fellow.<ref>https://www.mandelawashingtonfellowship.org</ref> He is also a  2018 Telemachus Fellow under the Global Thinkers Forum (UK). He is a  recipient of the 2018 [[Clarke International University]] Most Outstanding community outreach award.\n\n==Career==\n\nSharifu's career started in 2009 at [[Makerere University]] College of Veterinary Medicine Animal Resource and Biosecurity where he worked as a research assistant until 2010. He then moved on to work as a Biomedical laboratory technologist in the same university and department from 2010\u20132012.\n\nIn 2012, he worked at the Central Public health laboratory [http://www.cphl.go.ug/], Ministry of Health (Uganda) [https://www.health.go.ug/]. In 2013, he took on the role of Executive Director for the Uganda Sickle Cell Rescue Foundation, [[Kampala]]. In the same year, he also took on the role of assistant professor at the Institute of Allied Health Sciences at [[Clarke International University]], Kampala.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.sharifutusuubira.com/ \"Sharifu K Tusuubira\"] Official site\n*[https://www.irex.org/people/sharifu-kiragga-tusuubira \"IREX Sharifu K Tusuubira\"] Biography\n*[http://www.globalthinkersforum.org/people/sharifu-tusuubira/ \"Global Thinkers Forum - Sharifu Tusuubira\"] Profile\n*[https://ideasforus.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/Soluti \"sickle cell discrimination\"] Project\n*[https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(18)32357-2/fulltext \"Obituary for Dr. Lawrence Kaggwa\"] The Lancet\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:King, Zachary}}\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=March 2020}}\n\n{{short description|Uganda's sickle cell advocates}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Sharifu Kiragga Tusuubira\n| image       = Sharif Kiragga Tusuubira.jpg\n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = {{birth-date and age|January 4, 1991}}\n| birth_place = [[Kampala, Uganda]]\n| occupation  = Biomedical scientist, sickle cell advocate\n| spouse      = Sophia Nalubowa\n| parents     = Ashadu Zizinga and Ritah  Bazanya\n}}\n\n'''Sharifu Kiragga Tusuubira''' (born January 4, 1991) is one of [[Uganda]]'s leading [[sickle cell]] [[advocate]]s.<ref>Uganda young leaders-US Embassy, Kampala. [https://ug.usembassy.gov/ambassador-malac-parliament-speaker-rebecca-kadaga-flag-off-2017-yali-washington-mandela-fellows-uganda/ \"Speaker of Parliament, Uganda and US Ambassador to Uganda flag off, Mandela Fellows\" ] June 15, 2017,</ref> He is best recognized for his role in starting community sickle cell screening in [[Uganda]]. An initiative that enables people to take the sickle cell [[Screening (medicine)|screening test]] and receive results instantly from the confines of their villages.\n\n==Biography==\n\nSharifu was born on January 4, 1991, in Kampala to Ashadu Zizinga, a health inspector and Ritah Bazanya, a police officer.\nSharifu received his bachelor's degree in biomedical medical technology from [[Makerere University]] in 2012. He later went on to graduate with a [[master's degree]] in biomedical laboratory science and management  from the same university.  In 2017, he attended the Civic Leadership Institute at [[Kansas State University]].<ref>, Staley School of Leadership Studies [https://www.k-state.edu/today/announcement/?id=35106 \"Staley School of Leadership Studies to host Mandela Washington Fellows\"] June 13, 2017,</ref><ref>[https://blogs.k-state.edu/leadership/2017/10/12/mandela-washington-fellows-2017-civic-leadership-institute/ Mandela Washington Fellows: 2017 Civic Leadership Institute] October 12, 2017,</ref>\nHe was the first Executive Director of the Uganda Sickle Cell Rescue Foundation (USCRF)  a [[non-profit organization]] working to promote awareness, sensitization and fighting [[Sickle Cell Disease]] in [[Uganda]] <ref>The International Research & Exchanges Board [https://www.irex.org/people/sharifu-kiragga-tusuubira \"Sharifu Kiragga Tusuubira\"] March 2017</ref> (a position he held until July 2019).\n\n==Sickle Cell advocacy==\nSharifu Kiragga Tusuubira is a strong proponent for and an advocate of sickle cell and [[disability rights]] in Uganda.  His advocacy started while at [[Makerere University]] , following a personal heartbreak moment where a lady he was in [[love]] with, rejected him because of sickle cell. This motivated Sharifu to get involved and change the status quo of how the sickle cell was viewed.<ref>The Sickle Cell Warrior Diary [https://medium.com/@thewarriordiaries/the-journey-of-hope-from-wandegeya-to-america-sharifu-tusuubira-b24c3aefcfc3 \"The journey of HOPE from Wandegeya to America\"] September 27, 2019,</ref>\n\nFor over eight years, Sharifu has advocated for people living with [[sickle cell disease]] to have rights to independent thinking, participate freely in community activities or further [[Agency (philosophy)|agency]] and enjoy the same privileges as the \u2018normal\u2019 people in [[Uganda]] <ref>Young African Leaders Initiative [https://yali.state.gov/yali-voices-sharifu-tusuubira-champions-cause-living-sickle-cell-disease/ \"YALI Voices Podcast: Sharifu Tusuubira champions the cause of those living with sickle cell disease\"] December 2018,</ref><ref>The Daily Monitor [https://www.monitor.co.ug/Magazines/HealthLiving/Hope-for-sickle-cells-patients/689846-3282908-2e3i30/index.html \"Hope for Sickle Cell patients\"] July 7, 2016,</ref><ref>The Daily Monitor [https://www.monitor.co.ug/Magazines/HealthLiving/Medical-options-for-people-with-sickle-cell-anaemia/689846-2429224-1407nqs/index.html\"Medical Options for people living with sickle cell\"] August 14, 2014,</ref><ref>Uganda Sickle Cell Rescue Foundation [https://www.uscrfuganda.org/my-burden-is-my-purpose-without-it-i-wouldnt-be/\"My burden is my purpose\"] September 4, 2017,</ref><ref>Biomedical Central Public health [https://bmcpublichealth.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s12889-018-5496-4\"Knowledge, perception and practices towards sickle cell disease\"] April 27, 2018,</ref><ref>Adolescent health medicine and therapeutics [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6778728/\"To Join Or Not To Join? A Case Of Sickle Cell Clubs, Stigma And Discrimination In Secondary Schools In Butambala District, Uganda\"] October 2, 2019,</ref>\n\nLiving with sickle cell, Sharifu provides a firsthand narrative through his lived experiences to address issues of care, behavior, stigma, and discrimination among persons with sickle cell in different locales. Sharifu reached over 60,150 people, set up 18 support networks and registered 20,153 across the [[Uganda]].<ref>Global Thinkers Forum [http://globalthinkersmentors.org/sharifu-tusuubira-1 \"Leaders of Tomorrow - Sharifu Tusuubira\"] October 2018</ref> \n \nAcross the region, Sharifu has played a key role in supporting sickle cell advocacy.<ref>Betty Amamukirori [https://www.newvision.co.ug/new_vision/news/1424076/businessmen-contribute-sh50m-sickle-cell-fight \"Businessmen contribute sh50m towards sickle cell fight\"] ''New Vision Uganda'' 8th May 2016</ref><ref>John Muto-Ono P [http://www.blackstarnews.com/health/health/uganda-moves-to-fight-sickle-cell-disease-one-testing-site-serving \"Uganda moves to fight sickle cell disease\"] ''Blackstar news, Uganda'' June 21st, 2016</ref> Sharifu was instrumental in the launch of the East Africa Sickle Cell Alliance. He worked with the Pan African Sickle Cell Federation International to support grassroots initiatives and build membership across East and Central Africa.<ref>Gilmore Tee Show. Cliff Central.  South Africa [https://iono.fm/e/573872?fbclid=IwAR1lyGw_uNynvBaINU99uzisXJaL1prWlADfxRnyw6w6yUmcrO1TOjOEWdU \"World Sickle Cell Day\"] 22 Jun 2018</ref>\nSharifu is a 2017 Mandela Washington Fellow.<ref>https://www.mandelawashingtonfellowship.org</ref> He is also a  2018 Telemachus Fellow under the Global Thinkers Forum (UK). He is a  recipient of the 2018 [[Clarke International University]] Most Outstanding community outreach award.\n\n==Career==\n\nSharifu's career started in 2009 at [[Makerere University]] College of Veterinary Medicine Animal Resource and Biosecurity where he worked as a research assistant until 2010. He then moved on to work as a Biomedical laboratory technologist in the same university and department from 2010\u20132012.\n\nIn 2012, he worked at the Central Public health laboratory [http://www.cphl.go.ug/], Ministry of Health (Uganda) [https://www.health.go.ug/]. In 2013, he took on the role of Executive Director for the Uganda Sickle Cell Rescue Foundation, [[Kampala]]. In the same year, he also took on the role of [[assistant professor]] at the Institute of Allied Health Sciences at [[Clarke International University]], Kampala.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.sharifutusuubira.com/ \"Sharifu K Tusuubira\"] Official site\n*[https://www.irex.org/people/sharifu-kiragga-tusuubira \"IREX Sharifu K Tusuubira\"] Biography\n*[http://www.globalthinkersforum.org/people/sharifu-tusuubira/ \"Global Thinkers Forum - Sharifu Tusuubira\"] Profile\n*[https://ideasforus.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/Soluti \"sickle cell discrimination\"] Project\n*[https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(18)32357-2/fulltext \"Obituary for Dr. Lawrence Kaggwa\"] The Lancet\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:King, Zachary}}\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Hood 64M1", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sharifu_Kiragga_Tusuubira"}
